			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Router Connection Problems<a name="65735"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 5 04 7:47 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Go into the router and set port forwarding and triggering as such:
<br />

<br />
Application: EverQuest
<br />
Port Ranges: 1024 to 65535
<br />
UDP: Yes
<br />
TCP: Yes
<br />
IP Adress: (Set this for each machine by the assisgned IP's)
<br />

<br />
To find your IP on each machine....
<br />

<br />
Windows 98, Go to Start, Run, type winipconfig
<br />

<br />
For XP/2000, same as above but type IPconfig instead.
<br />

<br />
If you are running XP, disable the onboard firewall, it's trash anyway. Go to My Network Places, View My Connections, Double-click LAN, Advanced Tab, Disable XP Firewall by unchecking it. (If you are using a Network Bridge, double click this instead of LAN)
<br />

<br />
Then, Google for Zone Alarm, download that for a good firewall and set EQ as an allowed program to bypass.
<br />

<br />
This should fix 90% of your problems.
<br />

<br />
Also, go into your EQ folder and allow the game to use larger packets by doing the following:
<br />

<br />
Open the location of your EQ folder, Open the DataRate.Txt file. Change it from 5.0 to 9.0.
<br />

<br />
If you get some game lag from going to 9.0, drop it .5 at a time until the lag goes away.
<br />

<br />
If you use an active virus scanner you probably have an open process even if the program is closed out. This causes a lot of crashing/LD's also.
<br />

<br />
To check for that CTRL+ALT+DEL , click processes tab. Look for the name of your virus software in a file such as for AVG (what I use) it is avghost.
<br />

<br />
mcafee is mcfhost (or close to it)
<br />

<br />
Norton is NAVhost.
<br />

<br />
Turn the process off when you play the game, when you are done, just open the program from your programs list and then close (if you wish) to restart the process.
<br />

<br />
I have found through several different traceroutes and memory leak tests that these virus programs, even though closed can cause a great deal of packet loss and memory leak.
<br />

<br />
Hope some of that helps.
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
