			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Router Connection Problems<a name="65753"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 5 04 11:31 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>No offense Sannka, but regardless of using ZA or not, you just violated almost every internet security principle you could.  For those people using a router, leave your protection on. Firewalls generally only stop connections that are being initiated externally, (some routers can be configured for ingoing/outgoing firewalling)  connections which are initiated from inside your local network do not normally get affected by firewalls. (i.e, EQ generates the connections from inside the network)
<br />

<br />
Forwarding all your ports to the local machine is essentially turning your computer into a DMZ. This is a &quot;Bad Thing&quot; (tm) Relying on a software firewall to protect you is going to chew up resources on your local machine, and software firewalls are not infallible. The best option is use a software firewall in conjunction with a hardware one. (such as found on your router)
<br />

<br />
In most cases, problems such as you describer are related to ISP issues, or other users/processes eating up all your available bandwidth, cutting EQ out. Check for things such as spyware regularly, and keep an up-to-date virus checker on your system. Some people experience delays and computer 'crunching' with virus detectors enabled, so you may want to disable it while you play EQ. Ensure you regularly scan your PC if this is the case.
<br />

<br />
Despite the flack that Microsoft get, the firewall isn't actually all that bad, especially the XP SP2 one. It is very limited in configurability, yes, and it defaults to allowing certain ports such as MSN etc to be open, but for the 'average Joe' user it is quite adequate.
<br />

<br />
But I do want to say again, forwarding all your ports above 1024 to your local PC is a very bad thing. I would highly recommend NOT doing this.
<br />

<br />
The rest of the stuff is worth trying. In general, turning off your virus protection is pretty safe (in small doses) as the primary form of infection these days is e-mail and file downloads. Common sense can help you avoid the e-mail viruses, but with file downloading you're totally on your own. If you run behind a router, and you DON'T forward all your ports, then you are pretty safe from Internet based viruses. 
<br />

<br />
P.S. I hate Nortons Internet Security Suite with a passion, as do many people I know, however, some people swear by it. *shrug* </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
