			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Router Connection Problems<a name="65769"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 6 04 4:29 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I would suggest that if your router supports it (the Linksys should, it is a cut down linux kernel) is to only forward those packets from the EQ servers.
<br />

<br />
The following link shows you all the IP ranges, and has some helpful advice too.
<br />
<a target="_new" href="http://eqlive.station.sony.com/support/tech_support/ts_network_support_firewall_proxy_info.jsp">http://eqlive.station.sony.com/support/tech_support/ts_network_support_firewall_proxy_info.jsp</a>
<br />

<br />
There is <b>no need</b> to forward all packets (either UDP or TCP) specifically to a machine in your local network.  As has been stated, this puts your machine in the DMZ, which is not a good thing if you aren't a network guru.
<br />

<br />
If you can't filter by IP address, then my advice as a jobbing network guru is to get a new router<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-14.gif" border="0" alt="Devil" hspace="2" /> 
<br />

<br />
2 machines behind a NAT firewall playing EQ will work , I use this configuration all the time.  Updates during game time are generally UDP. This is a broadcast datagram, so all machines in your local subnet will get them if they want em.  TCP connections will always be initiated by the client (i.e. eqclient) so the router will know what to do with packets associated with that connection anyway. </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
